column81: You may have noticed that sometimes the program did not seem to label the numbers correctly. Can you state, in your own words, in as much detail as possible, why you think the program failed on these items?
Because the written numbers where not clearly written
The picture looked like another number and some of the human examples were not very clear either.

It is possible that the program failed to correctly recognize a few numbers because of the way it was written. sometimes an incorrectly written 0 can look almost like a 6, and a poorly written 8 can look like a 9. I think the program did it's best to get the correct answer from the poorly written numbers that were displayed.
Some numbers can appear to resemble other numbers when written quickly or carelessly. The program could only learn from and rely on what it has seen and been taught.
The main issue was either in reading/not reading smaller lines used by the writer, it wasn't consistent with picking up small imperfections
The samples shown weren't very clear and I think a human would have made their best guess at the same tasks as there was ambiguity.

Some numbers when not written clearly are incredibly similar such as a 7 and a 1. Additionally when the program is given human labeling examples of poorly written fives then it can end up confusing well written six for a five

I think it was given bad examples. Generally when it got a number wrong it's because the handwritten examples had been mislabelled or they were closer to another number than the number they'd been labelled as. It's fair of it to assume that a 1 is actually a 7 if all the examples of 7s that it's seen have looked very similar to that 1. I'm sure this would improve with lots more learning though.

I believe that the program sometimes labelled the numbers incorrectly because the hand written numbers weren't always clear, and in some cases they were badly composed. It is understandable that in the cases were the numbers learnt from were badly written and unclear, that the program would easily confuse them.
Due to humans not writing clearly
The human input was ambiguous, an example would be the number 1 that looked a bit like a number 7 and the spiral that could have either been a zero or a six.
Human handwriting differs and even human judgment can be wrong when identifying due to various factors.
I think the program failed on some items because the examples it had previously been shown for the number it labelled were similarly drawn to the number it was meant to be.
rotated and unfinished
The numbers were deceptive.
Maybe it needed more examples to learn from
It cannot discerne human variations.
4 and 7 if the 7 has a horizontal line are often mixed up if written badly. I would say the program is not yet as good a human, as the human can pick up handwriting style from the wider text
Poorly drawn numbers

Because sometimes humans write numbers in a weird way, and although it is easy for other humans to see what they intended to write (most of the time), the program is pulling from examples it has stored. And sometimes the actual number won't resemble an example the program has. It will stronger resemble a different number and so the program goes with that. It is easier for humans to make guesses on what the number is and I think that is why the program mislabelled more than me.
Apparently people dont know how to write 0 properly.   The program can only act based on what it is given. Some people have sloppy hand writing, and can make numbers appear similar to others.
Some of the human labels were poorly drawn and erratic.  they did not fit into previous examples given to the program, hence the errors.
